body:
It has the potential to break things if misused so I've made it an opt-in feature.
Right now it's used in a few simple cases (function call and single assignment).

---------------------------

Fixes https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/3253 and fixes https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/1612 (on modern compilers). My real interest is that it can be used to reduce unnecessary copies of C++ objects on https://github.com/cython/cython/pull/3323.

On pre C++-11 compilers it generates copies as normal, so non-copyable types will continue to fail as before.

----------------------

New version of https://github.com/cython/cython/pull/3359 since I force-pushed and so can now never open the original again apparently.

comment_data.body:
I found this name confusing in relation with `move_result_rhs()` ("as RHS"? why do we turn the value into a RHS here, and from what?).

I suggest naming it `move_result_rhs_as(type)` and putting it next to `move_result_rhs()`. It's really the same thing, just with a type cast. And then the argument should be mandatory.

I've removed the `assert` that this was trying to avoid. This part of the code was replaced in https://github.com/cython/cython/pull/3377 and so it's no longer looking at the types at all here.

I'd tried to assume that a call to `result()` should happen after the temp has been moved (which would be a nice assumption for safety, but right not I don't think it's generally true).

comment_data.body:
It does seem the wrong way round. I've changed it to assuming we can't move if type is `None`/unknown. I've also excluded types with `needs_refcounting` (which didn't exist when this PR was created, but I think makes sense).

I think this PR is more about adding a mechanism to support moving temps rather than covering every possible case, so it's better to be cautious now and use it more later if it turns out to make sense.

It would force me to change the interface of `calculate_result_code` because that doesn't have `code`.

I think the place to put it might be in `generate_disposal_code` since at that stage we have the code and know if the temp was moved (but this does relying on it anyone who overrides it remembering, and the disposal code being called correctly)

commit.message:
Added mechanism for moving rather than copying C++ temps

Right now it's used in a few simple cases (function call
and single assignment)

Fixed a couple of failing tests

Don't attempt to remove reference types.
Be wary of the "safety check" for double moves when things like
result() are called twice

Fixed cpp_temp_assignment text c++03 fallback

Made sure fallback option was genuinely c++03 complient so
that test should pass on clang
Add to utility_code generator to generate_post_assignment_code
